|archive-date=11 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211082553/http://www.wou.edu/las/physci/ch412/natwater.htm|url-status=live}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aluminium salts are nontoxic.{{citation needed|date=May 2021}} [[Aluminium sulfate]] has an [[Median lethal dose|LD&lt;sub&gt;50&lt;/sub&gt;]] of 6207&amp;nbsp;mg/kg (oral, mouse), which corresponds to 435&amp;nbsp;grams for an {{convert|70|kg|abbr=on}} person,&lt;ref name=&quot;Ullmann&quot; /&gt; though lethality and neurotoxicity differ in their implications.&lt;ref name=&quot;shaw14&quot;&gt;{{cite journal
|title=Aluminum-Induced Entropy in Biological Systems: Implications for Neurological Disease|year=2014
|last1=Shaw|first1=Christopher A.|last2=Seneff|first2=Stephanie|last3=Kette|first3=Stephen D.
|last4=Tomljenovic|first4=Lucija|last5=Oller|first5=John W.|last6=Davidson|first6=Robert M.
|journal=Journal of Toxicology|volume=2014|pages=1–27|pmid=25349607|pmc=4202242|doi-access=free|doi=10.1155/2014/491316}}&lt;/ref&gt; Andrási et al. discovered &quot;significantly higher Aluminum&quot; content in some brain regions when [[necroscopies]] of subjects with Alzheimer disease were compared to subjects without.&lt;ref name=&quot;andrasi04&quot;&gt;{{cite journal
